Uniform access principle is nice to have in JavaScript, a dynamic language like you pointed you. One of the nice things is it makes refactoring a bit easier. Imagine you have code that reads:<p><pre><code>  person = {
    name: &quot;ryan to&quot;,
    first: function() {
      return this.name.split(/\s/)[0];
    },
    last: function() {
      return this.name.split(/\s/)[1];
    }
  }
</code></pre>
But you realize this could be harmful, so you want to change it to:<p><pre><code>  person = {
    name: function() {
      return this.first + &quot; &quot; + this.last;
    },
    first: &quot;ryan&quot;,
    last: &quot;to&quot;
  }
</code></pre>
All of a sudden your code breaks because person.name needs to become person.name(), person.first() to person.first, etc. That is somewhat hard to track down/refactor in a large JavaScript code base, or any dynamic language code base for that matter.<p>Uniform access principle is, in my opinion, one of the selling points for implementing your own object model in JS.
